Consul. On the expulsion of Tarquin, the seventh and last king of Rome, Rc. 509, two magistrates were annually chosen and entrusted with the chief power of the state. All others, with the exception of the Tribunes of the Commons, were subject to them. They convened the Senam, assembled the people, and laid before them what they pleased, and executed their decrees. In the time of war they possessed the su- preme command. They levied soldiers, appointed the Military Tribunes in part (part being created by the people)‚ the centurione, and other officers. The legal age for the attainment of the consulship was sorty- three; but before it could be held it was requisite to have passed through the inferior offices of Quaestor, AEdile, and Praetor.1f one of the Consuls died during office another was appointed (suffectus or sub- rooatus est)1n his place. Within the city twelve Lictors went before each of them, alternately, for a month. A public servant, styled Accen- εἰιε, preceded the other, and the lictors followed him. Great respect was paid to them. People went out of their way, uncovered their heads, dismounted from horseback, or rose up as they passed.
